               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-997" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-997" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-997" type="surname" value="MORRIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-997" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH MORRIS</persName>
                  </hi>. The an apprentice to John Robinson, a tailor, of Sey<lb></lb>mour-street, St. Pancras. The prisoner came in on the 26th of January, at a quarter before eight o'clock for a penny-worth of silk—I told him we did not sell trimmings; but they did over the way, at the haberdasher's—he said, "I thought you sold silk, seeing it hanging up there, two needle fulls would do: and then he said thread would do, it was to mend his father's coat—he pressed me so long. I let him have a skein for 1 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>., the threw</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183602010175"></xptr>
               <p>down 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>—I went into the parlour for change—a witness said she would go for change—the prisoner said, "I will go"—the witness said, "No, I will go"—the prisoner held the door in his hand to go, and she insisted upon going herself—when we opened the door, we saw the waistcoat, which the officer has, outside, on the step of the door—it had been on the bar in the window—I had seen it safe about six o'clock—there had only been one other person in the shop, who came to pay a bill—I am sure he did not remove it—I was there when the prisoner first came in—he left the door wide open, and I told him to shut, it, because I heard the rings on the brass bar move, and I thought the wind blew the curtains—when we found the waistcoat, outside, we found there was another gone—we then asked the prisoner where he lived; he said, "No 3, Compton-street, "and he was found to live at No. 1, Compton-place.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-998" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-998" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-998" type="surname" value="FREEMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-998" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN FREEMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of James Freeman. I offered to go for change—the prisoner said, no, he would go—he went to the door and tried to stop me from going out—I got past him; and when I got to the step of the door I picked up the waistcoat, and accused him of taking it—he said it was not him, it was a boy at the door.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi> There are some more boys at the window, and it was one of them who who took it—they said it was a bad shilling—the door was open—when he was serving me he said he heard the window go.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
